1. Introduction

This document provides a comprehensive technical implementation plan for the Hybrid Drone and Missile Interceptor (HDMI) based on the QUENNE STACKED INTELLIGENCE architecture. It builds upon the previously defined system architecture and technical specifications, outlining the detailed steps, methodologies, resources, and timelines required to transform the conceptual design into an operational system.

The implementation plan follows a hybrid V-Model and Agile approach, balancing rigorous systems engineering with iterative development for AI and software components. It covers the entire lifecycle from concept refinement through to production and in-service support.

---

2. Implementation Objectives

· Deliver a fully functional HDMI prototype that meets all performance and operational requirements specified in QSI-HDI-001.
· Validate the integration of all nine QUENNE intelligence layers in a real-time embedded environment.
· Achieve certification for military operations (NATO interoperability, airworthiness) within 5 years.
· Establish a scalable manufacturing capability for series production.
· Ensure ethical compliance and nuclear safety through rigorous testing and formal verification.

---

3. Implementation Approach

3.1 Development Methodology

· Systems Engineering: V‑Model for hardware and system‑level integration, with strict traceability from requirements to verification.
· Software Development: Agile (Scrum) for AI/software modules, with two‑week sprints and continuous integration.
· Hardware Development: Spiral prototyping with incremental capability builds.

3.2 Key Principles

· Model‑Based Systems Engineering (MBSE): Use SysML models to manage complexity and traceability.
· Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment (CI/CD): For software, with hardware‑in‑the‑loop (HIL) testing.
· Digital Twin: Maintain a high‑fidelity simulation environment parallel to physical development.
· Open Architecture: All interfaces defined and documented to allow technology insertion.

