5. Detailed Implementation Phases

Phase 0: Concept Refinement (Months 1–6)

· Activities:
  · Finalize system requirements with stakeholders.
  · Develop detailed MBSE models (SysML) capturing all interfaces and behaviors.
  · Perform trade studies for key technologies (e.g., morphing wing mechanisms, quantum processor selection).
  · Establish digital twin environment integrating Aerodynamics, Structural, and Control models.
· Deliverables:
  · System Requirements Document (updated)
  · Interface Control Documents (ICDs)
  · Trade study reports
  · Digital twin baseline

Phase 1: Subsystem Design & Prototyping (Months 7–24)

1.1 Airframe & Propulsion (WBS 3.0)

· Detailed Design:
  · Finite element analysis (FEA) for morphing wing and fuselage.
  · Computational fluid dynamics (CFD) for aerodynamic optimization.
  · Design of ramjet inlet and nozzle with variable geometry.
· Prototyping:
  · Manufacture subscale models for wind tunnel testing.
  · Build full‑scale structural test article for static and fatigue testing.
  · Develop hybrid propulsion test rig (electric motors + ramjet).
· Key Milestones:
  · PDR (Preliminary Design Review) – Month 12
  · CDR (Critical Design Review) – Month 18
  · First full‑scale airframe assembly – Month 24

1.2 Avionics & Sensors (WBS 4.0)

· Design & Selection:
  · Specify and procure COTS sensors where possible (radar, EO/IR, LIDAR).
  · Develop custom nuclear detector (HPGe) with integrated cryocooler.
· Prototyping:
  · Integrate sensors on a sensor testbed (ground vehicle or aircraft).
  · Conduct field trials to validate detection ranges and accuracy.
· Key Milestones:
  · Sensor suite PDR – Month 12
  · Sensor integration testbed operational – Month 18

1.3 Computing Hardware (WBS 5.0)

· Photonic Processor:
  · Partner with vendor (e.g., Lightmatter) to customize for airborne environment.
  · Develop thermal management for photonic chip.
· Electronic Processor:
  · Design carrier board with Xilinx Versal, memory, and high‑speed I/O.
· Quantum Co‑processor:
  · Integrate compact cryocooler and quantum processor (e.g., Rigetti).
  · Develop interface electronics for control and readout.
· Key Milestones:
  · Computing hardware PDR – Month 12
  · First engineering samples – Month 20

1.4 Software & AI Development (WBS 6.0)

· Agile Development:
  · Set up CI/CD pipeline with HIL simulation.
  · Develop each QUENNE layer as containerized microservices.
  · Train AI models using synthetic data from digital twin.
· Key Milestones:
  · Software architecture review – Month 9
  · First end‑to‑end simulation of full stack – Month 18
  · Alpha release of AI modules – Month 24

Phase 2: Integration & Ground Testing (Months 25–36)

· Integration Lab (Iron Bird):
  · Assemble all subsystems on a ground test rig.
  · Validate electrical, data, and control interfaces.
  · Perform HIL simulations with real hardware.
· Structural Testing:
  · Full‑scale static and fatigue tests on airframe.
  · Morphing wing cycle testing.
· Propulsion Testing:
  · Ramjet ground test (tied‑down) at simulated altitude.
  · Electric motor endurance test.
· Software Integration:
  · Incremental integration of AI modules with hardware.
  · System‑level functional tests.
· Key Milestones:
  · Integration lab operational – Month 26
  · First complete system power‑on – Month 28
  · Ground vibration test – Month 30
  · System Functional Configuration Audit – Month 34

Phase 3: Flight Testing (Months 37–60)

3.1 Envelope Expansion

· Phase A – Low‑Speed Tests:
  · Tethered flights, then free flights with electric power only.
  · Validate takeoff/landing, basic handling.
· Phase B – Transition Tests:
  · Gradual wing sweep and ramjet ignition at altitude.
  · Validate booster fusion algorithm.
· Phase C – High‑Speed Envelope:
  · Incrementally increase speed to Mach 3+.
  · Test thrust vectoring and high‑g maneuvers.
· Phase D – Weapons Integration:
  · If applicable, test dummy intercepts against target drones.
· Phase E – Operational Demonstrations:
  · Multi‑ship cooperative engagements.
  · Nuclear threat detection drills.
· Key Milestones:
  · First flight – Month 38
  · First supersonic flight – Month 44
  · First successful intercept – Month 50
  · Operational test readiness – Month 56

Phase 4: Certification & Qualification (Months 48–66)

· Airworthiness:
  · Military airworthiness authority review (e.g., NATO, national).
  · Compliance with STANAG 4671 (UAV airworthiness).
· System Safety:
  · MIL‑STD‑882E hazard analysis.
  · Functional safety assessment (ISO 26262 for electronics).
· Cyber Security:
  · Penetration testing and certification (e.g., Common Criteria).
· Ethical AI Validation:
  · Independent red team evaluation of TRIAD AI.
  · Formal verification of ethical rules using model checking.
· Nuclear Safety:
  · Review by nuclear regulatory authority (if applicable).
· Key Milestones:
  · Safety case submission – Month 52
  · Airworthiness certificate – Month 60
  · Final operational capability – Month 66

Phase 5: Production & Deployment (Months 61–84)

· Manufacturing Setup:
  · Establish assembly line with automated composites layup.
  · Supply chain qualification for critical components (quantum chips, photonic processors).
· Low‑Rate Initial Production (LRIP):
  · Produce 10 units for operational testing and training.
· Full‑Rate Production:
  · Scale to 50 units/year.
· Training:
  · Develop simulator and training courses for operators and maintainers.
· In‑Service Support:
  · Establish sustainment logistics, spares, and software update pipeline.
· Key Milestones:
  · Production readiness review – Month 64
  · First LRIP delivery – Month 68
  · Full operational capability – Month 78

